'''''The Mothman Prophecies''''' is a 1975 book by [[John Keel]].&lt;ref&gt;Keel, J. 1975. ''The Mothman Prophecies''. New York: Saturday Review Press and E. P. Dutton. 269 pp. {{ISBN|0-8415-0355-9}}.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Synopsis==
The book relates Keel's accounts of his investigation into alleged sightings of a large, winged creature called [[Mothman]] in the vicinity of [[Point Pleasant, West Virginia]], during 1966 and 1967.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|first=E.L.|last=North|date=1979|chapter=Mysteries in the Mountains and Skies of West Virginia|pages=190–196|title=Redcoats, Redskins, and Red-Eyed Monsters|location=New York City|publisher=[[A. S. Barnes and Company]]|isbn=0-498-02085-1}}&lt;/ref&gt;  It combines these accounts with his theories about [[Unidentified flying object|UFO]]s and various [[supernatural]] phenomena, ultimately connecting them to the collapse of the [[Silver Bridge]] across the [[Ohio River]] on December 15, 1967. Official investigations in 1971 determined it was caused by [[stress corrosion cracking]] in an [[eyebar]] in a suspension chain.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=cJ1eAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=MVMNAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=4537,3056163|newspaper=[[The Portsmouth Times]]|date=28 May 1976|page=12|title=Claims In Disaster Denied}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Film==
{{main article|The Mothman Prophecies (film)}}
''The Mothman Prophecies'' was the inspiration for the [[The Mothman Prophecies (film)|2002 film of the same name]], starring [[Richard Gere]].

