The '''Limpopo River''' rises in [[South Africa]],&lt;ref name=&quot;EBLimpopo&quot;&gt;{{citation |work=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |title=Limpopo River |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Limpopo-River |access-date=2018-04-29}}&lt;/ref&gt; and flows generally eastwards through [[Mozambique]] to the [[Indian Ocean]]. The term Limpopo is derived from Rivombo (Livombo/Lebombo), a group of Tsonga settlers led by Hosi Rivombo who settled in the mountainous vicinity and named the area after their leader. The river is approximately {{convert|1750|km|mi|0}} long, with a [[drainage basin]] {{convert|415000|km2|sqmi|-2}} in size. The mean [[Discharge (hydrology)|discharge]] measured over a year is 170 [[Cubic metre per second|m&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;/s]] (6,200 [[Cubic foot per second|cu&amp;nbsp;ft/s]]) at its mouth.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book |last= Nakayama |first= Mikiyasu |title= International Waters in Southern Africa |year=2003 |publisher=United Nations University Press |isbn=92-808-1077-4 |pages=9}}; online at [https://books.google.com/books?id=Ittv1oAJ37sC Google Books]&lt;/ref&gt; The Limpopo is the second largest [[river]] in [[Africa]] that drains to the Indian Ocean, after the [[Zambezi|Zambezi River]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}

The first European to sight the river was [[Vasco da Gama]], who anchored off its mouth in 1498 and named it Espirito Santo River. Its lower course was explored by [[St Vincent Whitshed Erskine]] in 1868–69, and Captain J F Elton travelled down its middle course in 1870.

The drainage area of Limpopo River has decreased over [[deep time|geological time]]. Up to [[Piacenzian|Late Pliocene]] or [[Pleistocene]] times, the upper course of the Zambezi River drained into the Limpopo River.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |last1=Goudie |first1=A.S.|author-link=Andrew Goudie (geographer) |date=2005 |title=The drainage of Africa since the Cretaceous |url= |journal=[[Geomorphology (journal)|Geomorphology]] |volume=67 |issue= |pages=437–456 |doi= |access-date= }}&lt;/ref&gt; The change of the [[drainage divide]] is the result of [[epeirogenic movement]] that uplifted the surface north of present-day Limpopo River diverting waters into Zambezi River.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |last1=Moore |first1=A.E. |date=1999 |title=A reapprisal of epeirogenic flexure axes in southern Africa |url= |journal=[[South African Journal of Geology]] |volume=102 |issue=4 |pages=363–376 |doi= |access-date=}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Course ==
{{Location map
 |Mozambique
 |label=Limpopo River
 |lon_dir=E
 |lat_dir=S
 |lat_deg=25|lat_min=10
 |lon_deg=33|lon_min=35
 |position=right
 |width=250
 |float=right
 |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg
 |marksize=20
 |caption=Location of the Limpopo River's mouth
}}

The river flows in a great arc, first zigzagging north and then north-east, then turning east and finally south-east. It serves as a border for about {{convert|640|km|mi|0}}, separating [[South Africa]] to the southeast from [[Botswana]] to the northwest and [[Zimbabwe]] to the north. Two of its tributaries, the [[Marico River]] and the [[Crocodile River (Limpopo)|Crocodile River]] join, at which point the name changes to Limpopo River. There are several [[rapids]] as the river falls off [[Southern Africa]]'s inland [[escarpment]].

The [[Notwane River]] is a major tributary of the Limpopo, rising on the edge of the [[Kalahari Desert]] in Botswana and flowing in a north-easterly direction.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ugr.es/~natalie/mladenov/mladenov_notwane.pdf The Notwane River, Botswana]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}&lt;/ref&gt; The main tributary of the Limpopo, the [[Olifants River (Limpopo)|Olifants River]] (Elephant River), contributes around 1,233 million&amp;nbsp;m&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt; of water per year.&lt;ref name=Boroto&gt;Görgens, A.H.M. and Boroto, R.A. 1997. Limpopo River: flow balance anomalies, surprises and implications for integrated water resources management. In: Proceedings of the 8th South African National Hydrology Symposium, Pretoria, South Africa.&lt;/ref&gt; Other major tributaries include the [[Shashe River]], [[Mzingwane River]], [[Crocodile River (Limpopo)|Crocodile River]], [[Mwenezi River]] and [[Luvuvhu River]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/008/y5744e/y5744e07.htm|title=Drought impact mitigation and prevention in the Limpopo River Basin|author=|date=|website=www.fao.org|accessdate=5 April 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In the north-eastern corner of South Africa the river borders the [[Kruger National Park]].

The port town of [[Xai-Xai]], [[Mozambique]] is on the river near the mouth. Below the Olifants, the river is permanently [[navigable]] to the sea, though a [[Bar (landform)|sandbar]] prevents access by large ships except at high tide.

